All clean. Here's what was added for Railway deployment:

  Backend:
  - application-prod.yml — production config that reads Railway env vars (DATABASE_URL, REDIS_URL, PORT, etc.)
  - railway.toml — tells Railway to use Dockerfile with health check on /actuator/health
  - Updated Dockerfile with -Xmx512m memory limit

  Frontend:
  - Dockerfile.prod — multi-stage build (Node build → serve for static files)
  - railway.toml — uses Dockerfile.prod
  - src/api/client.ts — reads VITE_API_URL env var for API base URL (falls back to /api for local dev)
  - src/vite-env.d.ts — TypeScript types for Vite env vars

  To deploy:

  # 1. Install Railway CLI
  npm i -g @railway/cli
  railway login

  # 2. Create project
  railway init

  # 3. Add PostgreSQL + Redis plugins in Railway dashboard

  # 4. Deploy backend (from /backend dir)
  cd backend && railway up

  # 5. Set backend env vars in Railway dashboard:
  #    SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=prod
  #    JWT_SECRET=<openssl rand -base64 32>
  #    (DATABASE_URL and REDIS_URL auto-linked from plugins)

  # 6. Deploy frontend (from /frontend dir)
  cd ../frontend && railway up

  # 7. Set frontend build arg in Railway:
  #    VITE_API_URL=https://<your-backend>.up.railway.app

  For RabbitMQ, use CloudAMQP's free tier since Railway doesn't have a native plugin.

  ⏺ Your services are already accessible:

    - Frontend: https://frontend-production-37fc.up.railway.app
    - Backend: https://backend-production-63ee.up.railway.app

    Make sure the frontend's VITE_API_URL env var is set to https://backend-production-63ee.up.railway.app in Railway, otherwise API calls from the frontend won't reach the backend. If you change that var, you'll need to redeploy the frontend
    since Vite bakes it in at build time.

